 Down syndrome, as well as women who terminated their pregnancies because their fetus was identified as having the condition, Unexpected paints an intimate, nuanced picture of reproductive choice in today’s world. Piepmeier takes us inside her own daughter’s life, showing how Down syndrome is misunderstood, stigmatized, and condemned, particularly in the context of prenatal testing.At a time when medical technology is rapidly advancing, Unexpected provides a much-needed perspective on our complex, and frequently troubling, understanding of Down syndrome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren with Down syndrome. 0aFamily planningxDecision making. 0aMotherhood. 0aMothers of children with Down syndrome. 0aPrenatal diagnosis. 0aSociology of disability. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstreich, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGee, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479865468.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479865468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479865468/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles